{"id":"2208.00451","submitter":"Yash Sanghvi","authors":"Yash Sanghvi, Abhiram Gnanasambandam, Zhiyuan Mao and Stanley H. Chan","title":"Photon-Limited Blind Deconvolution using Unsupervised Iterative Kernel\n  Estimation","comments":"accepted at Transactions on Computational Imaging","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.IV","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Blind deconvolution is a challenging problem, but in low-light it is even\nmore difficult. Existing algorithms, both classical and deep-learning based,\nare not designed for this condition. When the photon shot noise is strong,\nconventional deconvolution methods fail because (1) the image does not have\nenough signal-to-noise ratio to perform the blur estimation; (2) While deep\nneural networks are powerful, many of them do not consider the forward process.\nWhen the noise is strong, these networks fail to simultaneously deblur and\ndenoise; (3) While iterative schemes are known to be robust in the classical\nframeworks, they are seldom considered in deep neural networks because it\nrequires a differentiable non-blind solver.\n  This paper addresses the above challenges by presenting an\n\\emph{unsupervised} blind deconvolution method. At the core of this method is a\nreformulation of the general blind deconvolution framework from the\nconventional image-kernel alternating minimization to a purely kernel-based\nminimization. This kernel-based minimization leads to a new iterative scheme\nthat backpropagates an unsupervised loss through a pre-trained non-blind solver\nto update the blur kernel. Experimental results show that the proposed\nframework achieves superior results than state-of-the-art blind deconvolution\nalgorithms in low-light conditions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 31 Jul 2022 15:14:22 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 2 Aug 2022 13:55:30 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 17 Nov 2022 23:05:49 GMT"}],"update_